# CVRP Solver with Travel-Time Costs

This repository contains a Python implementation of a Capacitated Vehicle Routing Problem (CVRP) solver where **travel time** is used as the optimization cost instead of Euclidean distance.  
The code is part of a research activity carried out within a **Marie Skłodowska-Curie Postdoctoral Fellowship (MSCA)** under Horizon Europe.

---

## Overview

- Solves CVRP instances where the cost matrix encodes **travel times** between nodes.
- Supports **CVRPLIB-style** input format, with an explicit (symmetric) cost matrix.
- Designed for **algorithm-selection / benchmarking**.
- Written in Python, intended for **reproducible research** and extension.

---

## Requirements

- Python ≥ 3.9  
- Typical dependencies:
  - `ortools`
  - `numpy`
  - `pandas`
  - `matplotlib`
  - `vrplib` (for CVRPLIB parsing)


HOW TO USE THE SOLVER

1) launch the script: python CVRP solver - travel times as cost - 14-11-2025 - cleaned.py
2) add the path to the CVRP instance when asked by the script. There is an example of CVRP instance in this folder.
3) insert the number of vehicles you have (or leave the minimum value)
4) choose the heuristics you want to use. Here there is the list:

AUTOMATIC
PATH_CHEAPEST_ARC
PATH_MOST_CONSTRAINED_ARC
EVALUATOR_STRATEGY
SAVINGS
SWEEP
CHRISTOFIDES
ALL_UNPERFORMED
BEST_INSERTION
PARALLEL_CHEAPEST_INSERTION
LOCAL_CHEAPEST_INSERTION
GLOBAL_CHEAPEST_ARC
LOCAL_CHEAPEST_ARC
FIRST_UNBOUND_MIN_VALUE

5) choose if you want to use a metaheuristics and the metaheuristics you prefer. Here there is the list:

AUTOMATIC
GREEDY_DESCENT
GUIDED_LOCAL_SEARCH
SIMULATED_ANNEALING
TABU_SEARCH
GENERIC_TABU_SEARCH

more info here: https://developers.google.com/optimization/routing/routing_options

6) Insert a timeout to stop the algorithm.

The Solver will plot the CVRP instance and plot the found solution. It will save the results in a json file, in the same directory.

NOTE: the CVRP instance you have to use must be in the VRPLIB format, with EDGE_WEIGHT_TYPE: EXPLICIT and EDGE_WEIGHT_FORMAT: FULL_MATRIX. you can find more info here:

https://github.com/PyVRP/VRPLIB?tab=readme-ov-file#vrplib-instance-format
